<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-simple-modules" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Simple modules</title>
    <introduction>
        <p>
            We define simple modules and study some of their properties. We begin with the definition of <sq>cyclic modules</sq>. Throughout this section, we assume that <m>R</m> is a commutative ring with unity and all modules are right <m>R</m>-modules.
        </p>
    </introduction>
    <definition xml:id="def-cyclic-module">
        <title>Cyclic module</title>
        
        
        <statement>
            <p>
                Let <m>A</m> be an <m>R</m>-algebra and <m>M</m> be a right <m>A</m>-module. We say that <m>M</m> is a <em>cyclic module</em> if there exists <m>m\in M</m> such that <m>M=mA</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </definition>
    <lemma xml:id="lem-cyclic-module-and-annihilator">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Let <m>A</m> be an <m>R</m>-algebra and <m>M</m> be a right <m>A</m>-module which is cyclic. Then,
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>M\simeq A/\Ann{A}{M}</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            If <m>N</m> is a right ideal of <m>A</m> then, <m>A/N</m> is a cyclic right <m>A</m>-module.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Let <m>N</m> be a right ideal of <m>A</m>. Put <m>B=\{a\in A:aN\subseteq N\}</m>. Then, <m>B</m> is a subalgebra of <m>A</m> containing <m>N</m>. Furthermore, <m>\End{A}{A/N}\simeq B/N</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </lemma>
    <proof>
        <p>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Suppose that <m>M=mA</m>. Define a map <m>\varphi\colon A\to M</m> by <m>a\mapsto m\cdot a</m>. As <m>M</m> is cyclic, the map is surjective and its kernel is precisely <m>\Ann{A}{M}</m>. The first isomorphism theorem for modules gives the required isomorphism.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Checking <m>A/N</m> is a right <m>A</m>-module is left to the reader. Consider the submodule of <m>N</m> generated by <m>1+N</m>. Given any <m>a+N\in A/N</m> we have <m>a+N=(1+N)\cdot a</m>, and therefore, <m>A/N\simeq (1+N)(A/N)</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        We first check that <m>B</m> is a subalgebra of <m>A</m> containing <m>N</m>. For <m>a\in B</m>, <m>n\in M</m>, and <m>r\in R</m> we have
                        <me>
                            (a\cdot r)n =a(n\cdot r), \text{as }n\in N\subseteq A\text{ and using algebra condition }<xref ref="eqn-algebra"/>.
                        </me>
                        The <m>N</m> is a right ideal of <m>A</m> and hence <m>n\cdot r\in N</m>. This shows that <m>a\cdot r\in B</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </proof>
</section>